The purpose of this notebook is develop a model that predicts whether a user will convert (buy) or not. The prediction has to be done at a session level, not user level. The data provided includes:

  1. transactions.csv: Information about different user sessions, such as the dates, number of relevant ads, number of searches done by the user

  1. user.csv: User id corresponding to each session id.

df['converted_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['session_dt'],errors='coerce', format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')
df['month'] = df['converted_date'].dt.month
df['day'] = df['converted_date'].dt.day
df['day_of_week'] = df['converted_date'].dt.dayofweek
df['is_weekend'] = df['day_of_week'].isin([5, 6])

In [12]:
# Due to cyclic nature of date and time, values which are close to each might be distinct in terms of raw numbers.
# Hence, we transform them to their cosine and sine values.

df['day_sin'] = np.sin(2*np.pi*df['day']/30)
df['day_cos'] = np.cos(2*np.pi*df['day']/30)

df['day_of_week_sin'] = np.sin(2*np.pi*df['day_of_week']/7)
df['day_of_week_cos'] = np.cos(2*np.pi*df['day_of_week']/7)

In [16]:
# Next, I wanted to check how many prior sessions a customer has
# I would would want to use this feature to predict if there is a certain number of sessions post which the user is more likely to buy the product

df = df.sort_values(by=['user_id', 'session_dt'])
df['prior_sessions_count'] = df.groupby('user_id').cumcount()
In [17]:
# Also, I wanted to see how many ads on an average a users sees before buying a product
# This could help in streamlining marketing and calculate cost to conversation

df['avg_ads_before'] = df.groupby('user_id')['num_impressions'].expanding().mean().reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
df['avg_ads_before'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
In [29]:
# Instead of average, I can take total number of ads too

df['total_ads_before'] = df.groupby('user_id')['num_impressions'].expanding().sum().reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
df['total_ads_before'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
In [18]:
# Similarly, I see how many searches the user has done prior to this session on an avergae

df['avg_search_before'] = df.groupby('user_id')['num_search'].expanding().mean().reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
df['avg_search_before'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
In [30]:
# Similarly, I see how many total searches the user has done prior to this session

df['total_search_before'] = df.groupby('user_id')['num_search'].expanding().sum().reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
df['total_search_before'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

Hyperparameter tuning using Grid Search and Repeated Stratified K-fold¶

In [242]:
model = LogisticRegression()
balance = [{0:100,1:1}, {0:10,1:1}, {0:1,1:1}, {0:1,1:3},{0:1,1:10}, {0:1,1:100}]
solvers = ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear']
penalty = ['l2']
c_values = [100, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01]
cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, n_repeats=3, random_state=1)
grid = dict(solver=solvers,penalty=penalty,C=c_values,class_weight=balance)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=grid, n_jobs=-1, cv=cv, scoring='roc_auc')
grid_result = grid_search.fit(X_valid, y_valid)

print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))

Best: 0.940211 using {'C': 10, 'class_weight': {0: 1, 1: 3}, 'penalty': 'l2', 'solver': 'newton-cg'}

fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_valid, y_pred_proba)

plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')  # diagonal line representing random guessing
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()
In [245]:
distances = np.sqrt((0 - fpr) ** 2 + (1 - tpr) ** 2)
# Find the index of the smallest distance
index = np.argmin(distances)
# Extract the threshold value for that index
optimal_threshold = thresholds[index]
print(optimal_threshold)

0.4749672811938333
